# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1896-temple-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1896-temple-cup/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th century's version of the **Baltimore Orioles** were founded in 1882 as part of the new American Association.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] Owned by wealthy Harry Von der Horst, the Orioles finished the season in last place with only 19 wins.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1896-temple-cup] The **1896 Temple Cup** was an end-of-the-year best-of-seven playoff between the National League champion Baltimore Orioles and runner-up Cleveland Spiders.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1896-temple-cup] The rematch of the previous year's Temple Cup began on October 2 and ended on October 8 with the Orioles sweeping in four games.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1896-temple-cup] In this third iteration of the Temple Cup, the Baltimore Orioles, who were also in their third Temple Cup, became the only team in the four-season Temple Cup to both win the National League pennant and win the Cup.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1896-temple-cup] Each winning player received $200, equal to $7,740 in 2025 dollars.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1896-temple-cup] The game was initially scheduled for October 1.
[src:1896-temple-cup/1896-temple-cup] Two runs scored by Baltimore in 9th inning not counted.
